The lower classes, represented by groups like Delta and Gamma, lack genuine autonomy, as their drive to consume and indulge is artificially strengthened through hypnopædia. This manipulation is orchestrated by the World Controller, exemplifying the concept of hegemony, where a dominant group exercises control over other social classes. The lower classes are oblivious to their manipulation, unwittingly accepting an ideology that perpetuates the capitalist structure. In contrast, the upper classes, represented by Alphas and Betas, are aware of their circumstances but often remain complacent, with few exceptions like Bernard.

In Brave New World, relationships between individuals are superficial, and the characters lack depth. This may suggest that the rise of technology and capitalism erodes human free will and self-expression. The novel's portrayal of interactions, often reduced to shallow comments about physical appearance, highlights the absence of genuine emotions and connections. Furthermore, the societal classes' acceptance of their positions in the hierarchy underscores the socioeconomic impact of capitalism, as they conform to their roles and obey the norms of their peers. This illustrates the Marxist concept of the proletariat, who are misled into believing in their own superiority as long as they continue to consume, obey, and conform.

I've been a student at University Park for almost three years, which is equivalent to five semesters. For many students, including myself, navigating the campus can be quite challenging. During my first year, I lived in East Halls, which is situated at the easternmost part of campus, excluding the stadium and the Bryce Jordan Center. The distance between my dorm in Stuart Hall and my classes in buildings like the Willard building, near the campus center, could take up to 25 minutes to cover on foot, especially on bad weather days, which are frequent in State College. I spoke to a recent alumnus who shared with me that not long ago, East Halls was separated from the rest of the campus by a large empty area. This vacant space has since been developed with sports fields, new buildings such as the Creamery and the health services building, and surrounding apartments. As the campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another is becoming increasingly difficult. In a college setting, I firmly believe that the most effective solution to this mobility issue is to use bicycles. However, owning a bike alone is not enough; students must be willing to ride them, and the campus infrastructure needs to be designed with the needs of cyclists in mind.

I recently spoke with a friend who had recently taken up cycling again after a several-year hiatus. He expressed his surprise that he had stopped cycling in the first place, stating that "cycling is the best way to get around." Besides being beneficial for one's physical health, cycling is the most efficient mode of transportation. Combining a nutritious meal, such as oatmeal, with moderate physical exertion can take you up to 30 miles or more. Like many of my fellow undergraduates, I now reside off-campus, which is just as far from the campus center as some dorms. My decision to purchase a bike has been one of the most practical choices I made this year. Every day, I attend classes in Thomas building, which is a 25-minute walk from my home. However, with my bike, I can reach the building in just 5 minutes if I pedal at a sufficient pace. The only drawback is that Pollock Road, which is the most direct route to Thomas building from my residence, is not always an easy road to navigate, whether by bike or on foot. While walking has its own advantages, I simply don't have the time for it. Without my bike, walking would be my only reliable option, and it would take me an additional 30-40 minutes each day to reach Thomas building. That's over two hours per week, which is a substantial time commitment. Considering the cumulative time spent walking to and from other classes, appointments, and other activities, it would be even more time-consuming. Given my schedule, I couldn't afford to spare that much time.
